cd - Changes the current working directory to a specified path.
Eg: cd /sdcard/Documents
​mkdir - Creates a new directory.
Eg: mkdir my_project
​ls - Lists the files and directories within a directory.
Eg: ls -la
​pwd - Prints the full path of the current working directory.
Eg: pwd
​touch - Creates an empty file or updates the timestamp of an existing file.
Eg: touch notes.txt
​cp - Copies files or directories from one location to another.
Eg: cp report.pdf /sdcard/Downloads/
​mv - Moves or renames files and directories.
Eg: mv oldname.txt newname.txt
​rm - Removes (deletes) files or directories.
Eg: rm file.txt
​rmdir - Removes an empty directory.
Eg: rmdir empty_folder
​cat - Displays the entire content of a file to the terminal.
Eg: cat config.json
​head - Displays the first few lines of a file.
Eg: head -n 5 data.csv
​tail - Displays the last few lines of a file.
Eg: tail -f logs.txt
​grep - Searches for a specific string or pattern of text within files.
Eg: grep "error" logfile.txt
​find - Searches for files and directories in a directory hierarchy based on criteria like name or size.
Eg: find . -name "*.py"
​chmod - Changes the file mode bits (permissions) of a file or directory.
Eg: chmod +x script.sh
​chown - Changes the user and/or group ownership of a file.
Eg: chown user:group file.txt
​ln - Creates a hard or symbolic link to a file.
Eg: ln -s /sdcard/data link_to_data
​df - Reports the amount of disk space used and available on file systems.
Eg: df -h
​du - Estimates the file space usage for files and directories.
Eg: du -sh my_folder
​file - Determines the file type of a given file.
Eg: file image.png
